    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start, but it feels a little too dry. Can you try making it slightly more personable? I don't want to sound like a robot, but I also don't want to get too mushy. Maybe add a line about how we'll keep his resume on file in case something more specific to his skill set opens up in the future?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You want it warmer, but still firm, like a friendly but very decisive head of a small, highly organized group. I can certainly inject a bit more warmth into that draft.\n\nHere is a revised version that adds a more personal touch and includes the note about keeping his resume on file. It feels less like a standard HR template and more like a genuine note from someone who actually enjoyed the interaction.\n\n***\n\n**Subject: Following Up on the Senior Developer Role at [Your Company Name]**\n\nDear Marcus,\n\nThank you again for investing so much time in interviewing for the Senior Developer role. I truly enjoyed our conversations; your technical insights and approach to problem-solving were genuinely impressive. It was a tough final decision, as you are clearly a very strong candidate. Ultimately, we decided to select someone whose experience was a slightly tighter match for the nuances of our current cloud architecture setup here in Austin.\n\nWhile this specific role wasn't the right fit this time, please know we were very impressed with your talent. We will certainly keep your resume on file, and if a role opens up in the future that better aligns with your specific strengths, we will absolutely reach out.\n\nWe wish you the very best of luck in",
      "source": "target",
